  "response": "No, not all caterpillars are butterflies. Caterpillars are the larval stage of both butterflies and moths, which belong to the order Lepidoptera. While all butterflies have caterpillar stages, not all caterpillars will become butterflies. Some will develop into moths. The key differences between butterfly and moth caterpillars include:\n\n1. Butterfly caterpillars eventually become butterflies\n2. Moth caterpillars become moths\n3. They have different characteristics in their larval and adult stages\n4. They belong to different families within the Lepidoptera order\n\nSo while every butterfly starts as a caterpillar, not every caterpillar will turn into a butterfly.",
